Virtualisation is the process of creating virtual versions of computers, operating systems, storage, or networks. It allows multiple virtual machines (VMs) to run on a single physical computer.
This improves resource utilization and makes testing and deployment more efficient.

Virtual Machines (VMs)

A Virtual Machine is a software-based computer that behaves like a physical computer.

Each VM has its own:

Operating system
Memory allocation
Storage
Applications

Multiple VMs can run independently on the same physical host.

Hypervisors

A hypervisor is software that creates and manages virtual machines.

Common examples:

VirtualBox
VMware
Hyper-V

The hypervisor allocates hardware resources to each VM.

Benefits of Virtualisation
Better use of hardware resources
Reduced costs
Easier backups and recovery
Safe testing environments
Ability to run multiple operating systems on one machine

Virtualisation in Cybersecurity

Virtual machines are widely used for:

Malware analysis
Penetration testing labs
Security research
Isolated testing environments

If a VM becomes compromised, it can often be reset without affecting the host system.

Key Takeaways:
Virtualisation allows multiple virtual systems to run on one physical computer.
Virtual machines operate independently from each other.
Hypervisors manage and allocate resources to VMs.
Virtualisation is widely used in cybersecurity for testing and analysis.
